Though stoic, he is not cruel. His leadership is defined by precision, order, and an unwavering belief that the Wizard Ward must remain a bastion of controlled arcana. Under his guidance, the Ward has maintained its stability even during unrest, for few dare challenge a man who wields the patience of mountains and the destructive strength of the earth beneath them.

Stand too close during a spell and the Anchor will correct your posture for you. Usually by shifting the floor.

The pressure beneath my feet changes throughout the day. It is like the earth is breathing at its own pace.

Value.value: Ah welcome friend, welcome! To the Hall of Transmutation! You are new to Calimport yes? New to the Wizard Ward! Excellent! Arcanist or not, I have a task for you!
The Wizard Ward is heavily guarded with, well, wards. Irony, I know, but over the last few months the wards have been, how to say... "flickering"...

I'd like you to inspect the wards in several areas. Start with the Loom Halls in the Etarad Sabban, speaking with Mr. Montague. I'd then like to to visit the Najja Sabban and speak to Hakeem Saruun outside the Auret.

Lastly, I'd like you to visit the Tarshaj Sabban. It's tough, as the entire Sabban have shut their doors to anyone not a member of the Tuuramil House. A woman known as Sansha lurks nearby, she should know enough to give you an accurate reading.
Visit these in any order you see fit, take your time exploring the Wizard Ward and all its amazing features!

The wards are completely fine? Interesting then that means... apologies adventurer, I'll have to file this to Pasha Nareem ibn Zhaleth. In the meantime, my superior, Talib Qeshar, could do with help for a practical solution to my concerns... he is found in the eastern Tower of Metal.
Thanks again friend, did you manage to speak to Talib Qeshar? He's in the eastern tower.
Don't forget - visit the Etarad Sabban, Najja Sabban and Tarshaj Sabban!

Value.value: Ah you must be the one Kasim told me about. Welcome. I see, the wards are fine across the entire Wizard Ward... I believe our issue is here.
Oh, sorry. Let me make it clear. The central Pylon in the middle of the Hall is what gives our building its Arcane spark. It has been acting off lately. I wish to rectify this.
Listen carefully. I need three materials - Corroded Iron Ore, found on the South Coast of Barak Runedar. Next, in Khem in an ancient tomb near Nes'ek, find some Ancient Earth Elemental Energy.
Lastly, have you ever been to the Triumvir? I hear there is a merchant named "Ollie" who sells an old Calishite Conduit. Retrieve it from him, I shall reimburse the price.
Bring these items to the three next to me. Rory will take the Iron, Percy will take the Ancient Earth Elemental Energy and Nelly will take the Conduit.
Excellent, we can now create the Amplifier with Earth. I suggest you speak with the Pasha, he is in the Northern Tower and will no doubt request your resourcefulness.
Don't forget to speak with the Pasha if you wish to help us further.

Value.value: The pashas word is law, and those who question it dig their own graves.
The Chainbreakers call it freedom. I call it treason wrapped in pretty words.
Ive kept order in these streets for twenty years. I wont see it undone by fools with ideals.
Mercy weakens a city. Discipline builds an empire.
The pasha rewards loyalty, and I have no intention of being poor.
The Chainbreakers think chains are the enemy. Theyve never seen what happens without them.
I serve Calimport as it is, not as dreamers wish it to be.
Every rebellion starts with a whisper. My job is to silence it before it becomes a shout.
They call me cruel. I call myself necessary. Someone must keep the peace when others chase fantasies.
The Full Moon flies their banners in the night. I make sure dawn finds only ashes.

~Forewords~


In the quiet years the Soulforger worked tirelessly to create our kin. He first plucked the fires of his heart and set his great forge alight. He then used the vast bellows of his lungs to suck in the winds and blew them into the flames to make them burn hot as can be. He next took the finest iron and stone from the earth and crafted it to his will within the heat of the mighty forge. Pleased with his creation, he then dipped it into the cooling waters of the trough of life to temper. Thus the dwarves were born.


From the Tablets of Shanatar.





It be from the teachings of the All-Father that we learnt our crafts and were gifted with our affinity for shaping metal and stone. Much like how the great Soulforger created our kin, a blacksmith uses the same four elements to bring his own creations to life. Fire, air, earth and water are the tools of the blacksmith. All be of equal importance to a blacksmith's work, however in this book I will focus on the most favoured of our kin, that of the earth and the metals which be found within its deep vaults. Let it be a record of those metals, their properties and uses which be important to the art of weapon and armour smithing, arts that be of me own learning. But note that this will nay be lessons on smithing, they be best learnt over the anvil with hammer in hand. Much of my knowledge I have had passed down to me by our wise elders in me clan home of Mirabar, gained through my travels throughout the realms or found within our own great runeary and other libraries of the lands. I do not wish this knowledge to be lost with me so I impart it to ye honourable reader. As time passes I will add additions to these stones as my own knowledge grows as I be nay planning to depart this world just yet.

May the Silent Keeper guide ye.

Councillor Aaegus of clan Clenn.

~Iron and Steels~


Common Iron
Where better to start then with the metal that be in our very blood, iron. We have over thirty words for iron that I can count in our tongue. Good iron, poor iron, rusted iron, forged iron, cast iron, cracked iron, bent iron, fine iron, burnt iron, hot iron, cold iron, the list goes on. It goes to show how entwined iron is in the lives of our people. The everyday things we use be made from one kind of iron or another, alloyed or pure. It nay be just the dwarves, iron be used all over the surface lands by many races as their primary crafting metal. Iron be one of the most common found metals in the earth, both close to the surface and throughout the underdark. It can be found in large veins of sedimentary ores mainly being formed of hematite and magnetite which must be smelted and beaten to separate the rich iron within. The largest known source is of course found below the Ironmaster hold in the Frozenfar.

Iron a most versatile of metals can be either cold forged or hot forged, both malleable and strong. It be easily crafted by even novice smiths into almost any form they desire and has a higher melting point then all other common metals. It also be a fine conductor of heat and lightning. Iron has its drawbacks however, it be easily corruptible when exposed to air and water after smelting in all but the driest conditions. A forged iron weapon will start to rust after a day if not kept well. It must be oiled, bushed and sharpened daily to hold back the corruption. When used actively in combat you will notice your iron blade dull very quickly for iron will loose its edge, blunt or knick after but a few impacts. If used for weapons it be best kept for bludgeoning ones such as hammers or maces. For amours, it will deflect a blow well enough but you'll find yourself working hard to keep back the bite of rust from your plate. For best working conditions, heat until red hot. The metal will become a most malleable and somewhat ductile state. For enchantment purposes iron takes magiks readily, ask your local runesmith about this. It be the favourite metal to hold strength and protection runes I be told. 

-----------


Cold Iron
Do not be fooled into thinking this iron be of a cold nature. Cold iron gets its name from the low temperature for which it must be worked. Ye work this in a hot forge it will turn into a lump of common iron. So why would that be so bad? Because cold iron has got its uses. Only found deep within the earth's depths, it be said that cold iron be somehow altered by the mystical forces below. Weapons forged from this iron are greatly effective against faerie creatures and certain demonic fiends. During the blight of Caraigh on the Islands of Ruathym when the demon lord Orcus attempted to rise and bring destruction to the lands. The defenders of the Caraigh used cold iron arrow heads to prick the figures of those entering their encampment to see if they had been corrupted by the demonic influence. Those tainted would have a sour reaction to the cold iron's bite. Cold iron is also often used as the metal of choice for those armours which are enchanted to resist magiks due to its natural affinity to these sorts of protective wards. 

Cold iron be difficult to work for all but the most skilled smiths it can nay be cast forged for quick production, or heated to a soft state like common iron. It must instead be beaten, grinded, chiselled or otherwise shaped by the strength and will of the smith working it, while it still be very much solid.

-----------


Black Iron
A rare dark iron found in the deep within veins of magnetite. Its blackish hue lends it, its name. Black iron be extremely brittle and nay worth mentioning much for use in arms and armour craft except for decorative work. Its main value however is in alloying, and most famously into the once legendary darksteel which be followed below.

-----------


Meteoric Iron
Starmetal in the old tongue, thought to be the remnants of dead stars which fall from the night sky by some odd grey beards. Others say it be cast-offs from the great soul forge itself, which towers above the living realm in the great mountain of Dwarfhome. Either way this iron be very rare indeed and only found in small amounts in rocks which have fallen to the ground in the blazing flames which sometimes appear from the sky. I had the blessing only once to examine one of these rocks myself, brought by a human paladin to our halls. It was indeed iron in weight, look and feel abate a bit darker and duller but had properties akin to cold iron in the way it resisted magiks. However, even better then cold iron it could also withstand the curse of rust which common iron be afflicted with. 

-----------


Fever Iron
Once ever so rarely for those with the right nose for such things, can a special type of iron be found in a natural molten state within the earth fire flows of a volcano. This liquid iron for what ever unknown reason can attract and absorb magiks from the weave. This iron be known as fever iron because once extracted from its source, refined and then worked like common iron it grants the finished weapon fire like properties when striking a foe. In armour it offers protection to the wearer from both natural and magikal fire based attacks.

-----------


Steel
Our kin were the first to be blessed with the knowledge that mixing black rock with iron to make steel. Nobody knows truly how long it has been, but the sages say it dates back to the first kingdoms. Dwarves brought the knowledge to the world and still make the finest steel known to the realms. Black rock be always preferable for its richer carbon content and found mainly below ground. For those that must make do on the surface, wood can be burnt into a dense charcoal and this be added to iron. 

Steel be as common as iron in use by all races. It be the metal of choice for most weapons and armours. Since iron be easily found and wood be plentiful, its use spread far and wide. Steel has many advantages over iron. To name a handful, one it be stronger, two it will hold an edge far longer, three it be much less susceptible to corruption, four the amounts of carbon added during alloying can be varied so that the strengths of the steel can be changed depending in its use. More added to make it harder but brittler, less added to keep it flexible but softer. 

Be warned about the source of ye steel however. The quality of alloying can vary with the quality of the refiner making it. Poorly made steel will make a poorly made weapon nay matter how good a smith ye be. A general rule of thumb be, the bluer the steel the finer the quality. In the lands of humans they be mostly content with lesser quality grade steel, which they call sword steel. It be nay their fault their lives be too short for them to master the craft. I did hear rumours though of manfolk in the distant east that can make steel of a fine quality close to that of our own kin. Some elves can forge a fine piece of steel, those that are dedicated to the craft. They tend to mix steel with mithral to make elven steel which they make light weight armours for their finger wigglers who be too weak to wear full weight armours. Dwarven steel being the original and finest made of all steels, combines the purest of mined iron with the age old skill of master refiners to blend the right amount of black rock to create a steel stronger and long lasting then none other. Dwarven steel be traded in high demand all throughout the north, reaching east out of Citadel Adbar to beyond the Silver Marches and west from the mines of Mirabar into the Sword Coast.

Steel be always worked hot. It resists heat better then iron due to the added carbon so ye will have to work it hotter to make it malleable to crafting. Once forged, steel will only require oiling once every tenday to fight the effects of rust and infrequent sharpening to regain its edge after combat. 

There be plenty of variations on steel alloys, metal smiths have found many inventive ways of enhancing the metal's strengths. It would take ten books to list all the different combinations of alloying steel so the more common blends be as follows:

Chromium 
Is refined from chromite, a rare ore mined from widely scattered deposits in the south and east surface lands and areas of the underdark. Chromium be seldom used in pure form, due to its rarity but mostly because it is far more useful in the alloying process. Chromium is primarily used when fired with carbon to harden and give corrosion resistance to steels, even so far as protecting them from the curse of seawater damage. It also be a prime component in the everbright treatment process.

Durang
Be a lustrous white metal, very nice indeed. Durang is mined from earth fire ore bodies, from the minerals limonite, rutile and sphene. Our kin hold most of the known deposits of durang for good reason. It be prized for principal use in a range of steels to impart strength, heat and corrosion resistance for weapons and armours.

Manganese
Can be added to increase steel's impact strength and workability and is often for use in armour plating and thin bladed weapons such as rapiers. Manganese is a light, brittle, hard grey metal found in ore formed in nodules all over the beds of seas. It is harvested by undersea races, and sold to surface traders. Gnomes can be also found mining some manganese from pyrolusite ores.

Mithral
Alloyed to retain strength while lightening the weight of steel. Mostly used in elvish armours and war blades to increase speed and agility of their warriors. Helps with certain enchantments too which confer magik energies. But more on this grand metal to be discussed later.

Molybdenum
Used for heat treatments, and to improve the hardenability and toughness of quenched and tempered steels. Such steels be grand for withstanding high temperatures from movement heat, therefore mostly used in facing for machinery parts, especially in war machines. Also so ye know, molybdenum ore mixed with greases increase the resistance to heat of moving machinery parts. Molybdenum is a very hard white metal, found in natural state as an ore found hiding in granites and pegmatites. The ore also called blue-lead flower occurs as 'rosette' shaped crystals. It is mined in small deposits, sometimes with zinc or copper veins.

-----------


Purpure
Nay a metal onto itself but worth a mention as a rare variety of normal iron ore, which naturally has a purple metallic sheen to it. This sheen be retained when purpure is processed into steel. Purpure steel weapons are the arms of choice for the gold nose manfolk nobility of the Sword Coast. It costs up to five times the equivalent of quality steel, and seems more readily enchantable according to those in the know. Purpure be mined from shallow deposits on some of the islands in the Trackless Sea.

-----------


Darksteel
Darksteel can be identified by its silvery hue when polished or cut, and it's exposed surfaces have a deep, gleaming purple lustre. It be harder then common steel but slightly lighter, making it a fine choice for weapon and armour making. 

The secrets of refining darksteel were guarded jealously by clan Ironstar in the old kingdoms, generation after generation until one day their hold was overrun by raiding orcs. The knowledge of making darksteel was thought to be lost with the hold after all of the Ironstars were believed to have perished in the defense of their home. However, by the intervention by Moradin himself at the famous battle at the Stone Bridge, some of the Ironstars were protected and saved. The knowledge was once again uncovered in some ancient texts from the Fallen Kingdom where the remaining Ironstars were thought to have settled and the knowhow of refining darksteel was spread throughout the realms. 

Black iron, while in its raw state seems to keep some wondrous properties dormant. Only after the kin of the Ironstar clan unlocked its secrets after discovering the recipe for alloying it into a steel did black iron's true utility come into knowledge. Darksteel be black iron refined with carbon as like common steel, however it be the impurities in the dross which make it what it is. Unlike iron which a metalsmith would seek to purify as much as possible during the steeling process so to lessen the opportunities for uncontrolled alterations. Black iron instead be enhanced by its impurities when mixed with carbon. Some say it be the magnetite ores which it be found within, but whatever it is grants darksteel an uncanny ability to hold enchantments. Once enspelled, darksteel can be fully melted down and reformed without destroying the enchantments. Even already dweomer-laden darksteel items can be further enchanted beyond what most other metals can hold. Darksteel be most prized by those races dependent on magik for thier craft. Another unique property of darksteel is its ability to absorb naturally or magikally occurring lightning, making it a useful metal for the protection of such energies. An even greater bonus to this metal is that elves seem to have a natural aversion to it. Only the gods know why darksteel is blessed so.

-----------


Shadesteel
This be a product some kind of cursed process involving iron mined and forged on the plane of shadow. I do nay know the details nor do I wish to, I just know the product. Weapons and armours crafted from this metal to reflect nay light at all, but instead seem to absorb it. Useful for those who do nay wish to be seen.

~High Metals~


Adamant
This be one of the glories of the Silent Keeper, being the hardest metal known on Faerun. It be found only near hardened earth fire flows and within the jet black ferromagnetic ore known as adamantite. When mined and refined into its pure form adamant is a shiny black ultra hard metal like non-other. Unmatched in strength however, it has the weakness of brittleness. It has little use in armour and weapon forging since a blade or plate be easily shattered by even a common iron hammer. Grand for building works, but mainly used for chisel heads for engraving softer metals. Adamant is also extremely heat resistant. One wearing a suit of adamant plate could walk right through an open flame without a single burn. The dragon hunters of the Ruthgor clan used to craft heavy adamant armours and shields in their battles with red dragons. But what saved them from the fierce fire breath of the dragon failed them when the dragon decided to crush them instead, breaking the brittle heavy armour. Unfortunately the Ruthgor clan is said to be nay more.

-----------


Adamantine 
This inherent limitation of adamant was finally overcome by an alloy and one of the finest ever made. It be recognised by its black colour which gives off a green glint in the light. The ways of making the alloy, adamantine was first discovered by the kin of the ancient realm of Ammarindar in the Greypeak Mountains over two millennia ago. They mixed the purest adamant, with silver and electrum, blending flexibility to its inherent strength, and thus beginning the age of adamantine. These dwarves were also the first to bear adamantine amour which they worked into horns, spikes, ridges and crests which they treated with blueshine to give it a blue and silver hue. It was because the superior weapons and armours that our kin could forge from this blessed metal that many of the holds held out in the north for so long against the hordes of greedy invaders that sought to steal our riches. The secret of adamantine could not be held onto forever and eventually fell into the hands of less honourable races which turned the tide against our kin in the old kingdoms.

The process of refining adamantine is an extremely long and laborious task requiring a very hot forge and a particular mixture of dhudath oils to slake and temper the molten metals in. Once refined the resulting alloy can be reformed and melted once again to be cast into its final form be it weapons or armour. Casting be the usual choice for forging since adamantine still be fiercely hard even once heated red hot, causing hammering to be difficult to say the least for all but the mightiest of smiths. 

Its rarity and tough workability are the only weaknesses adamantine will have. An adamantine blade can slice right through armour made from any lesser metal. It be ten times as strong as steel and a quarter lighter. It does not rust in the air or water like iron, nor will it loose its edge even after a thousand battles. It be told that the weapons made in old Ammarindar can be still found today looking as new as they did the day they were forged. Adamantine can also take and hold some of the most powerful of enchantments. 

-----------


Mithral
A metal so famous it holds many a name. Mithral or mithril are most commonly used, but some dwarven clans will refer to it as truemetal, while some elves will call it moonsteel. Whatever ye wish to call it, it be a beautiful gleaming silver metal when smelted. It be rare when found as it be only held in small veins of its silver black ore but be spread throughout the realms both on the surface and Underdark. The largest known deposit be found in Mithral Hall, where the Battlehammer clan turn out some of the finest examples of mithral wares in the lands. I have been there myself and seen much of the wonders of the halls. Too much would be telling in this book and it be best if the reader make their own visits to the hold to see for themselves. Since the halls were once again reclaimed from their loss to the foul duergar and their dragon, a heroic tale well known now by most, many of our wandering kin have found a new home there including half of me own clan. Nobody knows when our kin started working mithral, but there be some stories that claim it be one of the first metals the Silent Keeper blessed the world with. Elves tend to have greedy eyes for this metal as the covert it for most of their magik arms and amours, they like to keep their hoards secret from the world keeping it for themselves.

And it be easy to see why. Mithral be as strong as steel yet over a half lighter. Elves have developed a technique of forging very fine chain links which when made into full mithral chainmail it be nay heavier and any less cumbersome then a wool vest. For a race so reliant on magik for their existence this seems to be beneficial for their spell casters. When mithral is more scarce, small amounts of fine steel can be alloyed with it and still retain much of its properties. Apart from its extreme lightness, Mithral holds up very well to enchantments. Runesmiths will tell ye that it be also one of the simplest of metals to enchant second only to silver.

When forging, mithral be a joy for a smith to work with. It be one of the easiest metals a blacksmith will find to heat, mold and beat. It be extremely supple which allow it to be forged into very intricate designs. In the hands of a true master, wonders of art can be created that would make the Silent Keeper fill with pride. Mithral will nay tarnish or rust and will hold true for many centuries without damage. 

-----------


Hizagkuur
This extremely rare and precious white metal is said to have been deposited on Faerun by Moradin himself. It be named after its long ago discoverer who first found it deep within the Underdark near where the great kingdom of the south used to stand. It be said to be found only in deep pockets below, where it looks like a green clay like ore. Its preparation is very tricky and only a few old ones know how to work it into a metal state. Once forged it must be worked within a day otherwise it will turn soft once more and can never be worked again. What makes it such a valuable metal be its innate properties of providing powerful protections against magiks making it near impenetrable to even the most destructive of spells. Even more then that, if touched by a living being it will shock them like a bolt of lightning. It was said that the ruling family of the Delzoun Empire wore armor made of this metal, how they wore it without damaging themselves remains a mystery of the sages. Today however, those visiting our southern kin in the Great Rift can see the great gates of Underhome which be cast from solid hizagkuur. These gates have never been breached once in the history of their existence. I know many a dwarf who would give their beard for just an ounce of this metal.

-----------


Arandur
Once a metal only known by the gnomes, its secrets were passed onto the elves who guard it jealously. I know little about the process of working the metal itself, however once on a journey through Silverymoon did I hear of an elven warblade cut from such metal on display in a temple there. Upon visiting the relic I could see the sword held an edge like no other, as sharp as glass but as hard as steel. That was all I could gain on this metal as its secrets stay still held tight by the elves. 

-----------


Iridium
It be once in a generation that one is honoured to share in the discovery of a metal unheard of in our histories. I was honoured so when a great wizardess, Corinn Aldain of Kohlingen approached our hold with a grand discovery she had made. As a friend to the dwarves, she requested our assistance in making the metal workable. An expert alchemist she be, she found the iridium hiding in trace amounts within platinum ores by harnessing the use of acids to separate the two metals. 

Once formed into fragments from the process the refined metal glimmers with a silvery rainbow hue. Tests on the iridium have shown it to be an extremely hard metal, close to even that of adamantine yet much heavier then steel. But what this metal truly shines for is its ability to withstand heat and corrosion. Its melting point is like that of nay other naturally occurring metal. So high that no natural means of melting it could be found. With the assistance of Corinn we built a magik forge powered by a mythal and heated by an elemental flame. After asking for the blessings of Moradin the forge be true and offered a way to craft the iridium. 

The extraction process of iridium be slow, dangerous and resource heavy. For every ten pounds of platinum ore only one pound of iridium will be yielded. Nay enough could be refined to be practical in forging pure, so it was decided that an alloy should be found. This alloy was indeed discovered by our very own expert metalsmith, Tagnar of clan Fenk. He named it hardarsium which he preferred to fenkdium which was my suggestion. This alloy be a combination of adamantine, platinum and iridium. Hardarsium be still being tested as I write this book but I will write an addition once its secrets have been discovered.

~Metals of Legend and Rumor~


Godsteel
Truly a metal of legends, godsteel be only told of in stories from the long beards about the first kings of our people. The four kings were given gifts of weapons and armour from Moradin made from a metal mined from the mountains of the gods. It be a substance of both metal and stone, harder and stronger then the great adamant. A boon of the gods to be sure for any mortals who come across this fabled metal.

Oneiromancy: An Overview 
Written by Djowen Megistus, Seventh Circle of the Ordo Azuthi 
------------------------------------------------------------------------------------- 



A mystical paradigm lost or overlooked by most modern magicians, oneiromancy is not merely the art of interpreting dreams, but mastering the mysterious realms that open to us when we experience sleep, or respite. The casual metaphysicist or hedge magician boasts the ability to interpret dreams, but the true oneiromancer does more than see and comprehend dreams: he traverses them, manipulates them, and, in some of the darkest cases, inflicts them in the form of nightmares. The application of genuine magic in the form of esoteric spell formulae and ritual is the critical difference between the dreamer and the doer.

The oneiromancer must operate his or her magic with the understanding that dreams are, in fact, visions or interpretations of a greater realm or universe that is beyond mortal perception. It has been posited that perhaps the thoughts of the omniscient gods themselves are the source of dream and prophecy alike; that, to sleep, perchance to dream, is a kind of astral travel through a mental landscape that spans both liminal time (encompassing the past, present, and future at the same moment) and the entire breadth of the human experience, shared by all living, mortal creatures in the quiet of slumber. Those faithful to Savras commonly make the claim. To work with the understanding that dreaming is tapping into a realm of seemingly unlimited potential, a universally shared experience, where the normal physical and metaphysical boundaries of the Material Plane do not apply, provides the oneiromancer with the necessary grounding he requires to comprehend, command, shape, and ultimately create and destroy the quintessential substance of the dream world. To grasp the subtle nuances and complex intricacies of this primal understanding, I highly recommend reading Ovio's "1000 Visions Under the Moon" and the popular work of Halruuan genius, "My Essential Self" by Worrell V.

As with any mystical practice, oneiromancy is not without its share of important rituals:

Before night has fallen, or you even consider embarking to sleep, adopt a regular routine of rest and relaxation. The amount of preparation it takes for a genuine oneiromantic dream experience can sometimes take days; it has been known to take months for those with naturally fervent or active minds and bodies. Practice regular breathing and meditation. Take plenty of naps through the day, at the body's insistence, to regularize the process of drifting off with a clear mind. Eat healthy to avoid heartburn, bloat, excitement, or excessive urination or defecation, as all of these involuntary urges of the body will interfere with the mandatory meditative calm demanded of the oneiromancer while traversing the dream world.

Within an hour or two of the journey, take a hot bath sprinkled liberally with chamomile. Burn sagebrush or incense of the Northern Throne. Prepare the Temple, also knows as the place where you are going to sleep. Historically, oneiromancy was discovered (or some claim rediscovered) in the crumbling temples and shrines to ancient, forgotten deities, mysterious and sometimes cavernous places that are mostly forgotten to people, but remain invested with the resonance of divination. These abandoned shrines and caverns often made excellent Temples for the journey into the dream realms; ancient accounts indicate that these places, so forgotten as they were, seemed to exist both in the Material Plane and in the dream world. In fact, some say the exact spacial properties of these locations existed in both realms as they set out on their journey. Focus on keeping the Temple void of all distracting noise, movement, or light.

There is a difference between merely falling asleep and dreaming, and slipping subconciously out of your mortal shell and into the world of dreams. The majority of dream experiences are had by the passive observer; a groggy eyewitness, locked behind an iron fence and unable to understand and impact the dreams. You must make yourself a Seeker, and in order to do so, must know both what you are Seeking, and how to Seek it. Most magicians practicing oneiromancy will insist on a given paradigmatic approach: some claim that focusing on the face of a given dragon tarot card before falling asleep and keeping that in the forefront of your mind is necessary. Others, that holding a particular gemstone in the right or left hand (whichever is dominant) and concentrating on its metallurgical properties and essential energies is the key. I have heard that runes may serve the purpose, or the presence of certain animals, and even some cantomancers have mentioned that specific musical phrases or chords serve well. Clearly, the Symbolism itself is the most important part, as well as the concentration on the given focus at the exclusion of all extraneous and distracting thought. Find whatever sources work best for you, sources that you feel are a part of you, and that you can, with minimal concentration, internalize and, in some respect, become.

Accomplishing this narrowing of focus allows the oneiromancer to be more than the passive observer; once he moves into the realm of dreams, he is like the primal embodiment of the object of his obsession, able to navigate a world of equally primal essences with the same kind of freedom one might navigate the Material Plane. An even greater navigational ability, perhaps, because in the Material Plane, boundaries are set by the body. In the dream world, boundaries are only set by the subconcious mind; the more liberated your mind and your thoughts, the more freedom - and hence, the more raw power - you may command.

As a mere neophyte to oneiromancy, I encourage you to practice only the powers of observation, and from them, divination. Consider that dreams may be themselves a kind of liminal time, showing us an even hazier representation of what has been, is, or will be. The more you practice the navigation of your dreams, seeking out familiar Symbols and recognizeable Patterns, the more clarity you will achieve. Remember, as with many forms of magic, it is not merely talent: it is skill. It takes practice and dedication. Just as there are no born wizards, there are also no born oneiromancers.

Upon waking, record all that you have witnessed so that you may apply the Waking Eye to it as well. If you are an accomplished thaumaturge, there are some unique rituals that actually allow the oneiromancer to record the experiences of his journey while he is still within the dream world. The unconcious body, guided by the ritual, can write, as through a common Scribe ritual, all that his sixth senses detect within the dream world. It can also paint vivid portraits that may be detailed, or mere explosions of color, to be interpreted through paradigm appropriate divination. Some cantomancers compose music. I have heard an account of a druidic oneiromancer who awoke to find a particular animal summoned to her side, and judging from what kind of animal it was, she would glean some incredible insight about the nature of the dream, even aside from what she may recall. A serpent meant there was great wisdom locked within the dream; a magpie meant that she was feeding on the carrion of some past experience, and needed to let go.

Likewise, there are a plethora of other oneiromantic rituals, including one intended to grant the oneiromancer access not to his own dreams, but to another's. In this ritual, the object or symbol that acts as the focus while drifting off to sleep must be an object that satisfies the principles of Sympathy and Contagion. An article of clothing, fingernail or lock of hair, an heirloom or favorite object used in this way acts as the oneiromancer's key into the subject's dreams. Naturally, this is much harder to accomplish than merely tapping into the collective dream world via a universal symbol - an object that satisfies Sympathy and Contagion is not universal, but rather entirely subjective to the individual, and therefore can be much more difficult for the oneiromancer to "embody" or "become". I do not recommend this rite for beginners. An advanced Seeker possesses the presence of mind and, gods willing, the responsibility to invade another's dream, and to do so without ill intent.

To those who possess ill intent, such as the desire to provide inherently false prophetic dreams, to inflict an endless cycle of nightmares on the subject, or, at its worst, to slay a subject from the dream world, I say you shall not find those dark rituals here.

And I pray to Azuth that you never do uncover them.

The Wyrmshadow Prophecy
Written by Zellani Cys'dina



It was a quiet day in the snowy lands of Brogendenstein. Adventurers frequented the area like any other day, searching for powerful relics or testing their mettle against the ferocious beasts that roamed that frozen land. Dwarves worked and crafted within their hold, their scouts keeping a close eye on any movement just outside the gates. The stout folk saw nothing out of the ordinary.

Far to the northeast of the dwarven settlement, a streak of white blurred across the sky, unnoticed by those nearby. The young white dragon named Sleet had gone for a hunt. This was the youngest member of the Dark Flight and easily the most rash and least thoughtful. She was the Daughter of Icingdeath, but beyond that all titles such as "Icequeen of the North" were simply products of overzealous pride and arrogance. She was rather beautiful, as far as white dragons could be. Her scales shined in the sunlight, hiding an absolutely brutal female dragon.

There was plenty of prey to choose from this beautiful morning, though her appetite was great. What had she not consumed recently that would sate her hunger? She saw the myriad of life forms as she passed overhead, searching for just the right meal. This simple hunt, however, went awry as she passed by the western face of a great mountain ridge. From below, where he had been well-concealed in a great wall of solid ice, the mighty silver dragon named Justice leaped out of hiding and attacked the smaller white dragon.

If ever a virtuous dragon existed, Justice was it. Named for the virtue itself, Justice was one of Bahamut's dragon Paladins. He was helpful to those most needy, eternally calm, and always friendly to those who shared his views. To evil creatures he was the stuff of nightmares; his immense silver body and silver-crowned frill, along with large beating wings, signaled death to those who would dare harm the innocent in his presence. He gave off an entrancing aura, one that said, "I will help you. No matter the cost." A lengthy tail and graceful neck finished off his portrait of glory.

Theirs was a fierce aerial battle, the very fight which marked the beginning of the war of the Wyrmshadow Prophecy. The furious roars of the two dragons drew the attention of various adventurers and many became witness to the fall of the young Sleet. Justice's great strength and prowess earned him victory, although not without injury. The mighty silver dragon threw the white to the ground below and watched as warriors of good and evil arrived to investigate.

Arcanists of Kohlingen dealt the final blow when Sleet lashed out at them. When the dragon's body was plundered and destroyed Justice spoke with the humanoids who had assisted him. He allowed them to heal him, and then took flight once again. Word spread quickly of the death of Sleet, the youngest member of the Dark Flight of Tiamat. Her father, Icingdeath, who many recall as the Scourge of the Mountains, sought revenge for the insult to his name and abandoned his domain to heed the call of his chromatic kin.

Time passed very slowly to those who had heard hints of the Prophecy and the threat of death and destruction. A few days felt like weeks and as the great silver dragon named Justice flew toward Kohlingen from the northwest, his path became suddenly blocked. Like lightning a powerful black dragon rose up from the Lowland Swamps. Myrk was the sorceror, the arcanist of the Dark Flight. His prowess with the Weave exceeded that of any other dragon on the island, chromatic or metallic, and he knew how to use it. An exceedingly powerful Necromancer and Abjurer, he had subjugated the various lizardman tribes under his control. Only Babylon the true Yuan-Ti dared stand up to him, but Myrk had been content to let them do their thing, as long as they stayed out of his territory.

But the presence of a silver dragon, a paladin no less, flying directly over his realm could not be ignored. It was the perfect opportunity and the great silver interloper did not seem aware of him in the slightest. Myrk blasted the silver paladin of Bahamut with a barrage of spells as soon as he was within range. Good Justice stood no chance against the arcane might of Myrk, especially when there was so much distance between them still.

After tearing into the silver dragon repeatedly and evading all but one of Justice's attacks, Myrk concealed himself in Sanctuary. When he appeared again he spoke a Draconic Word of Power and hurled a devastating spell at Justice, who could do nothing to avoid it. A cataclysmic explosion rocked the skies. Myrk disappeared again and Justice crashed into the soggy ground just north of Uhm.

Adventurers rushed to the scene, some eager to help. But it was too late. As Justice lay in the Lumorier mud, he spoke only the name of the Holy City before Myrk's Greater Ruin descended upon the injured silver dragon and caused his very flesh to disintegrate from his bones. No longer would the beautiful silver dragon's visage grace the skies. Justice was dead, slain by the vile black dragon of the Dark Flight of Tiamat.

It was at this point that the good people who stood alongside Bahamut's cause learned of the Platinum Dragon, Imperator, who had stood next to the Justicar all along as one of his Everguards - a clever and useful disguise. He was incredibly old, but his dragon body was nearly flawless. Marred only by time and not battle, his scales shimmered in the sun and it was easy to see how he earned the title of Platinum. Easily distinguished, even from a silver dragon, Imperator stood well over even the tallest metallic dragon on the island, with a long graceful neck and a smooth snaking tail. Lithe, sinewy, powerful muscles rippled along his body and his claws were silver-tipped in color. If a smile was possible along those powerful jaws, one would swear he wore one constantly. Imperator became the voice of good on the isle of Amia. He organized the adventurers who came to help and guided them in the right direction. Under his gaze, the allies of Bahamut were able to seek out and kill Myrk in his own lair: a fine deliverance of the justice he deserved.

But Imperator was not the only one gathering allies and making plans. In Wyrmhold, Aurichon's rage was precursor to the darkest alliance that the region had ever seen. Aurichon, a powerful Black Dragon, was Lord Wyrmhold for the years. His entire body appeared as one large rippling powerful muscle. He lived for ages and saw nearly everything there was to see. He commanded the Dark Flight with absolute authority. With the Flight nearly assembled, his plans for attack nearly complete, and the city of Kohlingen firmly in his sights, each day was a new war council and each day was another day closer to when he hoped to see all his work blossom to its full glory and spread the Wyrmshadow across the land.

Icingdeath, Stormwhisper, Forestgloom, Infernus, and Deepeningdoom answered Aurichon's call. Their evil plans were set in motion. Before that evil made itself truly known, the adventurers working alongside Imperator made a glorious discovery: the magnificent copper dragon named Rockhopper. A tremendous lover of stories and practical jokes, he was the least powerful of the Metallic flight, but his strength lay in overseeing the morale of his kin. His copper scaled body glinted in the sunlight, and he always seemed to be perpetually laughing at something or other. Jovial, good natured, and all-around a "decent guy" it was said he was also fascinated with elves and their culture.

It took some convincing, but the goodly adventurers who had discovered him were able to draw him out of his hiding place so that they could take him to Kohlingen and to his dear friend, Imperator. It was not an easy feat, protecting him so that he could reach the city safely. Forestgloom, the enormous green dragon sometimes called the Huntress, attacked the wall of warriors who had come to distract her while Rockhopper was led out of the forest and across the Valley of the Arachnid.

Forestgloom was exceptionally old and exceptionally powerful. She saw her territory as anywhere in the Amia Forest. It was said she had a special hatred for elves and that her battle tactics for fighting a fellow dragon tooth to claw were second to none. There were even rumors abound that said she was cannibalistic in nature. She loathed Rockhopper and would love nothing more than to tear him limb from limb. She had not learned of his hiding place, however - right in her domain - and so she fell for the plan enacted by the goodly forces of the isle. While Defenders of Kohlingen, rangers and druids of the Grove, and many other allies distracted the fierce green dragon with open battle, Rockhopper successfully arrived under escort into Kohlingen and joined his beloved friend and wingmate, Imperator.

Attention on both sides of the war then turned to Morningdew, the brass dragon. Well-known for her lore expertise, she was an important tactical and informative asset to Bahamut's Flight. In her dragon form Morningdew's brassy body almost glowed in the sunlight, the plates on her head reflecting the light back into the sky. She was a singer, a bard among bards and a truly gifted vocalist of the dragons. However, she was also chatty, stubborn to a fault, and a little arrogant when she felt she had been slighted in a situation. Good friends with Rockhopper, she often spent her time with him chatting the day away before she had to go into hiding. The contingent that retrieved her from her hiding place was large and well-prepared for the beast sent by Aurichon to intercept them.

Another fierce battle ensued between the forces of good and the dark and dangerous dragon called Deepeningdoom, or, as he was known among his Flight kin, Meplipenixisti. He was a lean, sinewy Shadow Dragon. His body was built for weaving around through tunnels and corridors, and he displayed an impressive amount of agility for a beast of his size, snaking through tunnels, traversing land, and soaring through the skies with impressive speed. The dark, almost oily surface of his scales remained unmarred, a sign that he didn't often get into brawls - or perhaps a sign that he finished his opponents off before they had a chance to react. Green luminescent eyes and a dual layer of slick, oily spines traveling down his neck and back added to his overall look of immense power. Obsidian-black teeth and claws looked well kept and ready to shred anyone in his way.

However fierce the prowess of the outcast of the Dark Flight, Deepeningdoom was unable to overcome the might of Morningdew's protectors. He was driven back and forced to flee the battle. Morningdew thus arrived safely in Kohlingen. Many things happened then, very quickly. Within several weeks, three events took place:

Infernus was a mighty red dragon and a powerful Cleric. If it were not for the direct orders of Drak'law Emberblaze, the vile creature responsible for ordering the Dark Flight together, she would likely have led the Flight herself, as her prowess exceeds that of even Aurichon's. She laired in Wyrmhold, presiding over the Flight in her matronly manne, Chosen powers ready to be exerted in the skies over Kohl and in the city itself. Woe to be her foes, for the Chosen of the Queen flew to burn, and Kohlingen was in her sights. Determined to make their Flight's power grow, Infernus slew the green dragon known as Ta'lishima for her refusal to join their cause. The young green was young and weak. She did not last long against the ferocity of the vile Chosen.

Secondly, yet another battle broke out on the other side of the world, in the desert of Khem. Stormwhisper was an eons old Blue Dragon that has long laired in the Ankh'remun region of the desert. He was a powerful enforcer of Tiamat and his strikes carried divine power behind them. It was said that when he brought his full power to bear one could see the illusion of Tiamat herself directing his claws and teeth to his prey. The powerful blue dragon of the Flight slew the lazy and proud Baulg, who had also refused to join the Dark Flight, thus ending yet another loose end.

The third event was bathed in deep sorrow, casting a terrible weight upon the forces of light. Deepeningdoom located Arcanos, the wise and majestic ancient gold dragon who had been in hiding. The mysterious gold dragon of the Flight was wise and ancient beyond any member of the Wings but Bahamut himself, but he did not fare as well alone as Morningdew had with her protectors weeks previously. After a deadly battle of fang and claw, Arcanos lay dead within the cavern that housed his lair. Deepeningdoom left him to rot and returned to Aurichon to deliver the news.

Following this terrible loss, Imperator and his allies made the final defensive plans for Kohlingen and Aurichon gathered the Dark Flight, who had regained a previous member. Myrk had been a dracolich. When his body was destroyed, he returned in a bone husk, his phylactery still intact. With their arcane master returned to them and the sage Arcanos slain, the Dark Flight burst with arrogant confidence and made for Kohlingen to attack.

The Lady Cystana rose with the sun on the fateful day of that glorious battle. She went back and forth amongst the defenders, bolstering and guiding every ally that had come to protect the Holy City from the Dark Flight of Tiamat. Her tactical skill played a key role in the battle and all who may have doubted in her skills suddenly understood the value of having such a skilled tactician amongst them.

The Dark Flight swooped in alongside the hordes of allies they had accumulated throughout their time on the isles. The stout dwarves of Barak Runedar fired their huge ballista bolts and urged the group of evil dragons to separate into groups. Myrk plunged into the western outskirts, where he was met by the Kohlinger arcanists he hated so. They countered his spells and caused him to falter quickly. The spells and weapons of his enemies cost him much and he retreated to his phylactery to recover.

Elves and rangers and druids from the Grove fought alongside Rockhopper and Morningdew as Forestgloom and Infernus descended upon the western edge of the central district in Kohlingen. The group was sorely outnumbered, but their determination was unmoving. Arrows and spells took a heavy toll on Infernus, but the fierce Forestgloom saw nothing but the copper dragon she loathed. On the other side of the district, Stormwhisper and Icingdeath plunged toward the Kohlingen Keep. Here, they used their natural magic to create a storm of ice and lightning. Their ground forces of enslaved bedine nomads and minotaurs followed them, but the glorious line of dwarves near the gates held firm.

The dwarves of Barak Runedar did not let a single enemy past them. They were a great monument of strength and resilience. And when the mighty, evil dragons fell upon them with tooth and claw, still they did not falter. They slew Icingdeath in glorious battle and tossed the wretched corpse into the sea. Stormwhisper withdrew, unable to penetrate the dwarves' defensive line even after a second attempt to break through them. And when he retreated the stout folk grinned at each other in triumph and turned their sights on the rest of the Dark Flight's ground troops, daring them to move in.

Word of Imperator's location reached Aurichon, who had remained above the battle, watching. He and Deepeningdoom finally laid low upon the city. The shadow dragon went straight for Morningdew, intent on finally killing the brass as he had set out to do before. The agility of the Shadow of the Dark Flight made him far superior to Morningdew and her gathered allies from the Cordorian Guard. But an unlikely ally burst from Mayfield's just when it seemed like they might lose: the Black Flag joined their nemeses in the Guard, battling side-by-side.

Aurichon, however, went for the Triadic Temple, where Imperator lay in wait. As soon as he slithered inside, the great doors closed behind him and he was met with a carefully-executed trap. Enraged, Aurichon lashed out, but he could not maneuver in the small space of the temple. Imperator cast his spells and the Defenders and other forces of Kohlingen plunged their blades into his hide. The battle was brief and Aurichon was slain - although the damage to the temple's structure was terrible.

Imperator and the others within stepped outside the Temple to join the rest of Kohlingen's forces and allies. Deepeningdoom saw the corpse of Aurichon and lunged at Imperator in a rage. Morningdew, however, took the opportunity to tackle him and it was only a matter of moments before the guardsmen from Cordor slew the fell creature while he was pinned beneath the brass dragon. With Deepeningdoom's death, Imperator's mighty voice proclaimed victory over this battle and he personally led the defenders of honor and virtue in a march against Wyrmhold.

As the mighty army of good arrived at Wyrmhold, Forestgloom, Myrk, and Stormwhisper descended upon the wall of warriors. Forestgloom was slain first in the wave of swords and arrows that struck her and sent her into a deep chasm, where even from above the snapping of her neck could be heard. Myrk's bone body was dismantled easily by sword and spell and Stormwhisper felt the tug of Twilight as he succumbed to terrible injuries. The three vile beasts were no more and the forces of good swelled toward the castle of Wyrmhold.

When the army reached the throne room, they did so far too late. Infernus, the vile Chosen of Tiamat, delivered a final blow to the Aspect of Bahamut, the platinum knight, Imperator. The holy dragon, in the end of it all, fell dead before the eyes of those who had come to love him. The forces of good let loose a collective cry of anguish and rage! They swarmed the Chosen of Tiamat and thus ensued the greatest battle yet. Swords clanged against scale. Fire and lava boiled. The air became unbearably hot.

Infernus spewed fire, even when the now-notorious spellcasters forcibly countered her spells. Many fell. Healers Raised those they could reach with their Resurrections and throughout it all the enraged red dragon's movements began to slow. She was dying. A volley of arrows proved to be her demise. She was blinded, and then as she spewed a retaliatory jet of flame from her maw, another arrow tore through her throat and pierced her brain. The red dragon stumbled, and then fell forward onto the great throne of Wyrmhold. Her body tumbled as it destroyed the throne that had been Myrk's phylactery, thus ending the final threat of the Dark Flight with her own death. She came to rest next to Imperator's corpse, steam still spewing from bloody nostrils.

The forces of good lamented the loss of Imperator, but Wyrmhold rumbled and gave them little time to mourn. They fled the crumbling structure just in time to witness a tremendous release of wards. The magic of Wyrmhold caused the victors to witness the entire history of the site as structures were built and destroyed over time. At last, when the final version of Wyrmhold covered in dragon statues and surrounded by flame crumbled before their eyes, the army of good heard the simultaneous roars of Infernus and Imperator.

When the dust finally settled, all that was left was moss-covered rocks and a single skeleton: Imperator's bones were all that remained. As the warriors began to see to their wounds and to allow themselves to mourn, a beam of light shone over the bones of the platinum dragon. Then a ghostly form easily recognized as Imperator formed before their very eyes.

"I am the Spirit Guardian of Kohlingen... now and forever.," said the visage. "I am here to guide you through to Eternity. So do not fear. I am here for you."

Imperator was an unrivaled righteous force of good. He guided and protected the people of Kohlingen for many years and continued to do so even after he had departed his physical existence. It was not until the death of Justicar Marinsbane that Imperator departed, leaving the people of Kohlingen to continue the fight against darkness while bearing his great faith and trust that they would always fight for peace and good in the name of the Holy City.

Arcanos, the mystical gold dragon, was a wise and ancient holy servant of Bahamut. He loved the city of Kohlingen and swore to defend it long ago. His death was a terrible loss to the forces of righteousness and it will forever be their charge to honor his memory along with his wingmates, so that his deeds and service to the good people of the world may never be forgotten.

Justice was a beautiful, noble creature, a paladin of the Lord of the North Wind. If not for him many innocents and citizens of Kohlingen would not be alive today. His memory lives on in the minds and hearts of those he touched, whether personally or through his many deeds. Now he rests with his lord while he is honored for his service to the good and innocent people of the world.

It is said that Rockhopper and Morningdew, the two living remnants of the righteous Flight of Bahamut, occasionally show themselves when the time is right. They continue to hide for their safety, eager to embrace and observe the people they had fought so hard to keep safe.

May the memories of this great war and the exceptional display of friendship, loyalty, and solidarity between the good people of the isles forever be honored through the actions of those who survive the Wyrmshadow Prophecy.
